To bombinate in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Eloquence has always been one of President Barack Obama's principal assets.
It seems today that his words have cornered him into a dilemma.
After saying in March that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and mentioning last year a "red line" that should not be crossed, Obama will lose face if he does not react forcefully to the murder, attributed to the Syrian regime, of more than 1000 civilians using sarin gas.
Of course, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why on earth had Obama ensnared himself with such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
The U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry is right to describe the use of gas as "morally obscene."
But torturing children, precursors of the civil war two years ago, is just as heinous.
And killing civilians with chemical products is it more morally obscene than bombing them, shooting them, or letting them die of starvation?
It is commonly admitted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
The weapons of mass destruction, particularly nuclear bombs, certainly cause more damage and more quickly than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing around 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb in Hiroshima and killing even more in a single night in Tokyo with incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas the Jews than to shoot them in mass graves?
A viewpoint, defended notably by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, holds that a swift punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to abandon the use of chemical weapons and revert to "more mundane means for massacring his people."
In my opinion, it makes no sense.
The question is surely one of mass murder, not the methods used.
In all cases, moral outrage, justified as it may be, is not a sufficient reason to go to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the deaths of more than 40 million Chinese people in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sensible person has suggested that military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with the support of the United States.
Is it then a legal question? The use of chemical weapons constitutes, in fact, a violation of international conventions, including the Chemical Weapons Convention, which Syria never signed, and the Geneva Protocol, to which it is a party.
There are therefore valid reasons to consider Assad a war criminal, in which case he should be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), established, to be noted, by a treaty that the United States has never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not a readily defensible policy.
One could, however, argue that the "international community," or Western countries, or the United States as the main Western power, must surely draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn a blind eye when innocent people are mass murdered?
Tolerating a genocide is not acceptable.
But exactly where should a line be drawn?
How many murders constitute a genocide?
Thousands?
Hundreds of thousands?
Millions?
Or does the number not matter at all?
A genocide is, after all, a matter of intent; there is a will to kill or persecute individuals because of their race, ethnic affiliation, or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons – or even two – would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from another angle.
The question to consider before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance to improve the situation, save lives, and make the world a safer place.
Yes, the violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
Responding to this implies asking: What is the best solution?
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
Like the ICC, "humanitarian intervention" is more likely to produce results in a weak country (for example, Serbia, Mali, or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a great power.
No one would consider launching missile strikes on China or Russia in the name of defending human rights or enforcing international norms and conventions related to warfare.
Syria, as many have pointed out, is not Libya or Mali.
It is not a great power.
But the civil war that rages there has already spilled over its borders, involving more important countries such as Iran, Turkey, and Russia.
There can be no doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is absolutely not certain that an American intervention would reduce the risk of a wider conflict.
In fact, some supporters of American intervention – both neoconservatives and "liberal hawks" – seem to wish for the opposite: they call for a war with Iran.
And Obama likely drew a parallel in his mind between the red line concerning Syria and the one he drew for Iran, perhaps just as thoughtlessly, to prevent it from developing nuclear weapons.
What, then, can be expected from American strikes on Syrian targets, when Obama has already indicated that they are not aimed at bringing down the Syrian regime?
They will not end the civil war.
But a single missile strike will suffice to make the United States a direct participant in this war, triggering a resurgence of violence.
Taking this risk to salvage Obama's honor doesn't seem particularly wise.
This view is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
This is the opinion of most Europeans.
And from a majority of Americans.
This might even be Obama's own view, which is why he desperately tries to buy time by delegating to the American Congress the authorization to use military force in Syria.
Since taking office, his relations with Congress have not been easy.
But he needs it more than ever to cover his back.
